            <section aria-labelledby="mortgage-basics-heading" class="prose">
              <h2 id="mortgage-basics-heading">
                Mortgage basics in plain English
              </h2>
              <p>
                A mortgage is simply a loan secured by real estate. You borrow
                money to buy (or refinance) a home, and the property itself is
                collateral. If you stop paying, the lender can foreclose and
                sell the home to recover what you owe.
              </p>

              <h3>Key moving parts of any mortgage</h3>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Principal:</strong> The amount you borrow.</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Interest rate:</strong> The cost of borrowing,
                  expressed as a yearly percentage.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Term:</strong> How long you have to repay (e.g., 15 or
                  30 years).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Amortization:</strong> The schedule that splits each
                  payment into principal and interest.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Escrow:</strong> Extra amounts collected for property
                  taxes, homeowners insurance, and sometimes mortgage insurance.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  Monthly mortgage payment formula (principal &amp; interest)
                </p>
                <p>If:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\(L\) = loan amount</li>
                  <li>\(r\) = annual interest rate (decimal)</li>
                  <li>\(i = \dfrac{r}{12}\) = monthly rate</li>
                  <li>\(n\) = total number of monthly payments</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Then the monthly principal &amp; interest payment is:</p>
                <p>\[ M = L \cdot \frac{i(1+i)^n}{(1+i)^n - 1} \]</p>
              </div>

              <h3>Fixed vs. adjustable‑rate mortgages (ARMs)</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Fixed‑rate mortgage:</strong> The interest rate and
                  principal &amp; interest payment never change. This is the
                  simplest and safest option for most buyers.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Adjustable‑rate mortgage (ARM):</strong> The rate is
                  fixed for an initial period (e.g., 5 years in a 5/6 ARM), then
                  adjusts periodically based on an index plus a margin, subject
                  to caps.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                ARMs can make sense if you know you will sell or refinance
                before the first adjustment, but they carry more risk if rates
                rise or your plans change.
              </p>

              <h3>Understanding APR vs. interest rate</h3>
              <p>
                The <strong>interest rate</strong> is what your monthly payment
                is based on. The <strong>APR</strong> (annual percentage rate)
                wraps in many lender fees and closing costs and expresses the
                total cost of borrowing as a yearly rate.
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Use the <strong>interest rate</strong> to understand your
                  payment.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use the <strong>APR</strong> to compare loan offers with
                  different fee structures.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>How lenders think about affordability</h3>
              <p>Lenders typically look at two debt‑to‑income (DTI) ratios:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Front‑end DTI:</strong> Housing costs ÷ gross monthly
                  income (often targeted at ≤ 28%).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Back‑end DTI:</strong> All debt payments (housing +
                  other loans/credit cards) ÷ gross monthly income (often capped
                  at 36–43% depending on program).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Our affordability tools let you adjust these thresholds to match
                conservative or more aggressive underwriting guidelines.
              </p>

              <h3>Comparing loan types: conventional, FHA, VA</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Conventional:</strong> Best for borrowers with
                  stronger credit and at least 3–5% down. Private mortgage
                  insurance (PMI) usually drops off once you reach 20% equity.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>FHA:</strong> More flexible on credit and down payment
                  (as low as 3.5%), but mortgage insurance often lasts for most
                  or all of the loan term.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>VA:</strong> For eligible veterans and service
                  members. Often allows 0% down and no monthly mortgage
                  insurance, but charges a one‑time funding fee.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>When refinancing is worth it</h3>
              <p>
                Refinancing replaces your existing mortgage with a new one. It
                can make sense if:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  You can lower your rate or shorten your term enough to justify
                  the closing costs.
                </li>
                <li>
                  You plan to stay in the home long enough to pass the
                  break‑even point.
                </li>
                <li>
                  You want to switch from an ARM to a fixed rate, or remove
                  mortgage insurance.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Our refinance panel and dedicated calculator estimate your
                monthly savings, break‑even time, and total interest savings so
                you can make a data‑driven decision.
              </p>
            </section>

