                <div class="border rounded-md">
                  <button
                    class="w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium text-gray-800"
                      >Is it better to make a bigger down payment or keep more
                      cash?</span
                    >
                    <span class="text-gray-500 text-sm">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    A larger down payment lowers your monthly payment, reduces
                    total interest, and can eliminate mortgage insurance. But
                    keeping more cash can protect you from emergencies and make
                    it easier to handle repairs or job changes. Use the payment
                    and affordability tools to see how different down payments
                    affect your monthly budget, then weigh that against your
                    need for a safety cushion.
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="border rounded-md">
                  <button
                    class="w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium text-gray-800"
                      >How often do mortgage rates change?</span
                    >
                    <span class="text-gray-500 text-sm">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    Lenders can update rates daily or even multiple times per
                    day in response to bond market moves. Publicly posted
                    averages (like Freddie Mac's PMMS) are typically updated
                    weekly and give a good sense of trends, but your actual
                    quote will depend on your credit profile, loan type,
                    property, and closing timeline. Use our calculators with a
                    slightly higher rate than today's quote to build in a safety
                    margin.
                  </div>
                </div>
                <div class="border rounded-md">
                  <button
                    class="w-full text-left px-4 py-3 flex justify-between items-center faq-question"
